      },
      "date": "2018-04-19 17:44:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(2 comments)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2b452148b240420c8f6ed9a5cc4bea8e2b337bb5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-04-20 16:14:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> This looks like it should actually be MDS_ATTR_ATTR_FLAG,\n > since not all of the ATTR_* flags match with the MDS_ATTR_* flags.\n\nThat comment turns out to be incorrect, but now in the opposite direction.  op_attr is struct attr, so ATTR_* flags are correct.  The problem is that there is no \"ATTR_ATTR_PROJID\" in that namespace, so there is a risk of collision with other \"ATTR_* flags (the 0x8000 flag is currently used by \"ATTR_TIMES_SET\", as is seen in ll_setattr()).\n\nWe can't change the value of MDS_ATTR_PROJID, since this is already used over the network.  Instead, we should declare an ATTR_PROJID flag and map it properly in attr_pack(), like with ATTR_CTIME_SET, that avoids conflicting with other flags.  Since this is in-memory only (if handled correctly) it doesn't matter if it needs to be changed in the future, which is the whole point of keeping it separate from MDS_ATTR_* flags that need to stay the same forever.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    }
  ],
